    cat >> "$MD_FILE" <<EOF

# Engagement Methodology

## Attacker Model

This engagement emulated an insider threat actor who has gained physical or VPN access to the internal network. The tester was provided only with the target CIDR range(s) and no credentials, hostnames, or architectural information. This is consistent with a black-box testing methodology.

## Methodology Phases

The engagement followed a four-phase methodology consistent with industry-standard internal network penetration testing:

**Phase 1 -- Information Gathering.** The tester performed host discovery via ICMP ping sweeps, followed by a full TCP port scan of all live hosts. Service and version detection (banner grabbing) was performed on all open ports to identify exploitable services. MSSQL servers were identified through service banner analysis rather than port number alone.

**Phase 2 -- Focused Penetration.** Identified MSSQL services were targeted for default and weak credential testing using dictionary-based brute-force attacks. Successful authentication was leveraged to enable the xp_cmdshell stored procedure, providing operating system command execution. OS-level reconnaissance was performed on each compromised host (hostname, network configuration, local administrators).

**Phase 3 -- Post-Exploitation.** The SAM and SYSTEM registry hives were extracted from compromised hosts and NTLM password hashes were recovered. Persistence was established via Windows scheduled tasks configured to execute a reverse shell payload on system boot. Network interfaces on compromised hosts were enumerated to identify additional network segments.

**Phase 4 -- Lateral Movement and Cleanup.** Recovered NTLM hashes were used in Pass-the-Hash attacks against all live hosts in the environment. Known MSSQL credentials were tested for reuse against additional MSSQL instances. When a compromised host was found to have network interfaces on previously unknown segments, the Windows netsh portproxy facility was used to establish TCP port forwarding through the dual-homed host, allowing the attacker machine to reach services on the remote network. Initial reconnaissance of each new segment was performed from the pivot host itself using PowerShell-based scanning, followed by targeted port forwarding and execution of the full attack chain through the forwarded ports. After all testing was complete, all remote artifacts were reverted: portproxy forwarding rules were reset, xp_cmdshell was disabled, scheduled tasks and payloads were removed, temporary files were deleted, and registry modifications were restored to their original values.

EOF

